review_blob: 22oz in Trappist Glass. Pours a murky amber-brown with a creamy tan cratered head that has a nice thick webbed lacing. Scent is an eclectic combination of citrus, heavy maltiness, and light notes of yeasty mustiness combined with a light bitter hop complement. Taste is wide ranged and very complex... Initially very sweet in the mouth with a malty palate. This gives way to a medium bodied belgian character with a quick decline into sharp hoppiness and grain... Surprisingly smooth with a light bitter residue. A very unique beer- almost a tribute to opposites in attrraction. Has the character of an aggressive US Northwestern beer intermixed with the complexity and subtelty of a well crafted Belgian...

Bottle. Pours out a deep black colour with a mild creamy tan head. Moderate lacing. Nose is coffee and malt. Taste is slightly salty, coffee, and roasted malt with a nice ash/fireplace character on the palate and on the way down. Smooth and mdium-full bodied but slightly chalky on the palate after it has gone down.
beer_name: Great Divide St. Bridgets Porter (St. Brigids)

review_blob: Bottle. Pours out a hazy gold colour with a quickly receeding bubbly white head. Scent is pretty much strickly malted wheat. Taste is light bodied, if slightly abrasive, and has grassy notes. Definite malted wheat and an unfortunate ester funk.

Bottle to shaker (pounder). Pours out a gold-amber colour with a very nice foamy white head and excellent lacing. It is made from freshly harvested hops and only available about 3 months out of the year. Its nose is caramel and earth with light pine and definite hop elements.  Taste is sweet, appealing, and hoppy with a caramel backdrop. Finish is bitter and sweet with caramel notes and a pleasant grass element. Complex and very flavorful
beer_name: Great Divide Fresh Hop Pale Ale

review_blob: Bottle to shaker (pounder). Pours out a pale gold colour with a light creamy white head with nice lacing. Scent is light earth and sweet floral hops.  The hop is abruptly agressive and then quickly subsides to mild sweet hops. Taste is as above- abruptly aggressive hop elements with a grain element additionally intermixed. Mouthfeel is smooth and the finish is amazingly smooth if not a bit quick. A good brew overall but it unfortunately seems a bit short lived and relative to other stone brews slightly lacking in aggression.

Bottle to snifter. Pours a midnight black with a dark tan creamy meteor crater  landscaped head with excellent lacing. Scent is malty and roasted malt.  Taste is malty/roasted malt with a medium tasting yet full body. Lots of activity on the lips. Nice fireplace ash/smokyness element throughout drink. Goes down very smooth with lots of character and body.

Pours an  copper-amber colour with excellent clarity and a quickly receeding white head. Scent is yeasty with mild hop and earth as the backdrop. Taste is yeast and hops. Light apple/bannana elements. Tempo is flat and mostly one dimensional. Interesting flavor elements but otherwise unimpressive and the interesting elements dont match the style very well. Distinct lack of hop for its style as well.

Bottle to shaker (pounder). Pours a nice clear amber colour with a moderate foamy white head with moderate lacing. Scent is yeat and earth and hops with lots of activity. Definitely lacking in the hop element to warrant calling it an IPA . Finish is yeast and hops.

Pours a nice clear amber colour with an impressive foamy tan-white head with abundant bubbly lacing. Lots of in glass activity. Scent is hoppy, cinnamon, and coriander. Taste is very cinnamon  at first, quickly subduing and becoming sweet hoppiness. Body is light-medium and taste is mildly aggressive but overall amazingly flavorful.

Pours a clear amber colour with a quickly receeding white head. Moderate in glass activity. Scent is unimpressive and almost undetectable; light malt and nearly unnoticable hop. Taste is very grainy. After a bit of drinking a mild bannana element arises but aside from that there are no real stand out qualities.
beer_name: Flying Dog Old Scratch Amber Lager

review_blob: Bottle. Pours out a hazy yellow amber. Little head and no lacing. Nose is of peaches and tartness. Taste is peach and fruity sweetness.

Bottle. Pours a cloudy gold-orange colour with a fizzy active white head. No lacing. Scent is honey and apple and sweet and warm. Taste is sweet and mild bodied.Yeast and honey elements are most prevalent with slight boquet of citrus flavour in the backdrop.

Bottle. Pours out a deep black-tan with a mild creamy tan head with moderate lacing. Nose is very malty with elements of chocolate, coffee and surprisingly grape. Taste is thick bodied, creamy and malty with a fruity grape character that cuts through it lifting it up into a very drinkable beer. Very smooth going down with a fruity palate. Layers of complexity that marry very well.

Bottle. Pours a distinct golden colour with a quickly receding head. Little to no lacing and little activity. Scent is barley and malty... moderate flat smell with little character. Taste is mild bodied and contains little character. Sweet but mottled with a odd flavorless character.
beer_name: Flying Dog Tire Bite Golden Ale

review_blob: Bottle. Pours out a nice cloudy pinkish-red colour with an impressive rose-blush head with nice lacing. Nose is creamy and cherry with mild estery scent on the far backdrop. Taste is fruity and cherry... very very sweet. Is comparable to drinking a bottle of fruit juice in consistency plus a slightly more rounded body.

Bottle. Pours out a deep blood amber colour with a nice foamy-creamy white-tan head. Moderate activity. Nose is hoppy, grassy and a caramel/toffee element. Taste is very full bodied and hoppy. Palate is relativily smooth and caramel. The overall character is very aggressive but the palate tones it down to a manageable level making it very subtle and complex.

Bottle into pounder (shaker). Pours a hazy orange colour with an impressive foamy tan-orange head... plenty of lacing. Scent is sweet grapefruit hops and is very floral. Taste is orange, grapefruit, grassy bitter. Body is light but the overall impact is pretty potent. Leaves a strong astringency in the nose as it is drank and on the way down. Very drinkable and complex IPA.

Bottle to pounder (shaker). Pours out a light amber colour with a slight bubbly head with very minimal lacing. Scent is slightly nutty and dry. Taste is at first hoppy and sweet and then quickly progresses into spices and an almost pumpkin element. Goes down well but unfortunately leaves a dry and metallic element on the palate.

Bottle. Pours a crisp light amber with a quickly receding head with little activity. Scent is pumpkin, spices, cinnamon with a very mild unpleasant tang interwoven. Taste is tea-like containing pumpkin and cinnamon and nutmeg. Unfortunately there is a bitter metallic wateryness to it. It tastes as though it should be smoother but its character is waylayed by this harshness. It seems to have two distinct yet opposing elements at play. Not to bad but unfortunately its components did not marry very well.

Bottle into pounder (shaker). Pours a light apple juice colour with a quickly diminishing bubbly head with little activity. Scent is very light... It took a big whiff to pull in a light honey element. Taste is very sweet with pronounced elements of honey and apple. Goes down very smooth and leaves an almost green apple jolly rancher flavour on the palate. Overall is very sugary with a nice flavour balance... Lacks however in complexity. Very drinkable.

Bottle into pounder (shaker). Pours out a light yellow-gold colour with a bubbly bone white head. Lots of activity. Scent reminds me of play-doh and rubber bands with mild skunk as a backdrop. Taste is reminiscent of the inside of a trash can... All metallic followed by a metallic palate and a harsh bitter and metallic bite all the way down. No real flavour aside from metal and harsh water. I feel like Im stepping away from an attempt at objectivity and moving into the realm of slander when I say this but this beer is absolutely terrible... It has no redeeming qualities and you might well just drink out of your garbage can to get the same experience.

On Tap in a Weizen. Scent is of yeast and wheat malt. Cloudy bannana yellow in colour with a nice creamy white head with moderate lacing. Flavour is citrus, bannana, autumnal spices and wheat malt... Very interesting. Smooth character and lots of complexity... An exceptional hefe-weizen.

On Tap. Reddish-brown with a quickly receding tan creamy head with sparse lacing. Scent is definitely hoppy with a pleasant fruitiness to it. Taste is hoppy and floral on the tongue with a web of complex grain an hop interaction (it kind of acts in the mouth in layers).  Leaves a nice velvety texture on the palate and nice activity on the lips. Not an exceptionally outstanding ESB but it definitely had a nice smooth texture overall.

On Tap in Shaker. Light brown-amber colour with a sizable creamy white head with good lacing. Scent is subdued; smooth and inviting with strong tea elements. Taste was creamy and light/smooth bodied with strong tea elements intermixed with a nice balance of mild grain and hops. Interesting earthy flavour on the palate as it goes down.

Bottle to pounder (shaker). Pours out a mildly cloudy orange-brown with a nice fluffy light-tan head with nice lacing. Nose is sweet and hoppy with a malty backdrop... Not sharp, very floral and sugary. Taste is thickly bodied with grain flavour with a palate of maltiness intermixed with bitter hop character. Leaves a risidue of sharpness on the palate as it goes down.
beer_name: Big Sky Scape Goat Pale Ale

review_blob: Bottle to pounder (shaker). Pours out a nice yellow-gold colour with a slight bubbly head with sparse to nonexistant lacing. Strong aroma of lemony ester and grain held together by a mild hops note. Very mild overall scent with the exception of the estery compounds. Taste is malty, wheat, and yeast. Goes down smooth and is very drinkable, as seems to be the redhook style, but lacks slightly in marriages of elements. The elements do come together but they dont seem to be making any particular statement.

Bottle to pounder (shaker). Pours out a clear golden colour with a nonexistant head. Scent is mildly skunky and corn. Mostly the scent is subdued to nonexistant. Taste is flat and watered down with strong corn elements. A sort of sugar, rust and corn flavour on the palate as it goes down.

Bottle. Pours out alight amber colour with a nice bubbly white head with patchy lacing. Scent is pretty standard fare for an ESB... grain and sharp hoppiness unfortunately accented with a metallic tinge. Taste is smooth and hoppy. Starts out with a velvety texture and then proceeds independently into a sharp hoppiness. A light flavour of grain and metallic taste is left on the palate as it goes down. A very mild ESB that unfortunately has some unpleasant metallic qualities. Drinkable but not an outstanding example of its type.

1 Pint Can... Pours out an amber-gold colour with a nice creamy white head with great lacing. Scent is estery with elements of apple and grain. Taste is smooth and creamy with a nice apple cider flavour. There is a mild grainy backdrop on the palate that intermixes with the ester element. Very tasty with the exception of a mildly astringent quality in the backdrop of the beer that lingers a bit on the palate after the beer has been drank.

Bottle. Pours a crisp and clear copper amber colour with a nice billowy creamy head that laces well. Scent is spicy/cinnamon and yeast. Taste is mild bodied with cinnamon and hints of spices and pumpkin all of which leaves a pleasant and creamy residue upon the palate. A surpisingly good example of a good pumpkin ale, slightly lacking in complexity but a definite adherence and example of and to its style.
beer_name: Blue Moon Harvest Moon Pumpkin Ale

review_blob: Bottle into shaker (pounder). Pours out a hazy bannana yellow with an obviously intact trub. Head is slight and mildly creamy. Scent is very estery with a strong wheat backbone and a hint of a citrus element. Taste is very full bodied and surprisingly tart and sweet. definite wheat elements as well as hops, and a distinct fruitiness. Palate is sweet and fruity with a mild yeasty residue intermixed. Very complex flavour but not all of the elements marry perfectly... Still yet a good drink, and very drinkable as well.

Bottle into Pounder (shaker). Pours out a light golden colour with a bubbly a mild white head. Scent is skunky and corn. Taste is pretty much the same with a sweet palate that is interspersed with metal. Unimaginably plain and unexciting.

Bottle. Pours out a dark gold- almost brown tinted colour with an impressive fluffy white head. Very hazy. Scent is hoppy, grassy, and mildly yeasty. Mild patches of fruity notes carry on the carbonation. Taste is not very hoppy for an IPA but is very drinkable. Taste is caramel, grass, and hops with a sweet malty palate. Interesting interplay of flavours and very carbonated. Plus points for uniqueness... Minus points for lack of IPA character.

Bottle. Pours out a nice clear amber colour with a mild fluffy white head with lots of carbonation. Scent is strongly of caramel with a tap-waterish character and a backdrop of grain. Taste is sweet hoppy and malty. Not much complexity but a nice solid IPA... Seems to be a signature of Summit- not to push into new grounds but to make a nice moderate example of specific styles.

Bottle. Pours a light yellow-gold with a quickly receding bubbly head. Scent is yeasty with a mild skunky backdrop. Slight citrus expelled with the carbonation- almost just molecules of it. Taste is sweet and lightly hoppy with a floral aftertaste that brushes on the palate. Finish is grainy/wheaty flavours on the palate and sweetness on the way down.

Bottle. Pours out a hazy gold colour with a bubbly white head that is lacy but recedes fast. Scent is grainy and very mildly hoppy. Taste has a light to light-medium body with the carbonation leaving ticklers on the palate. Sweet flavour and slightly sour but not much complexity. Finish same as taste with a sourish residue. Easy to drink but lacking in diversity.

Bottle. Pours out a mild brown colour with a nice lacy off tan head. Scent is chocolate, malt, and light nutty notes. Taste is crisp and malty with a very mild hop backdrop. Palate is sweet and the beer is very drinkable. Nice brew but lacking slightly in complexities, but a fine example of a good brown
beer_name: New Glarus Fat Squirrel Nut Brown Ale

review_blob: Bottle to pounder (shaker). Pours out a clear gold colour with a frothy lacy white head. Scent is mildly hop skunky with a mild yeasty backdrop. Taste is mellow with a mild hop and tap water combo initially. Then it moves slowly into maltiness and an odd astringency. The finish is mildly sour followed by a relatively pleasant hop bitterness. Nice amount of elements and uniqueness but the individual elements dont marry very well when combined- almost a ceremony of opposites.

Bottle. Pours out a hazy orange-yellow colour with a nice foamy head. Scent is mildly hoppy with strong citrus elements that warm your nose as the molecules hang there comfortably.  Taste is coriander, orange, and lemon. Smooth on the palate and leaves a fruity sugaryness all the way down the throat.

Bottle. Pours out a nice caramel colour with an excessive white fluffy head. Scent is lightly of clove and cinnamon and yeast, all of which is very subtle. Taste is very sweet with a strong yeasty estery character. Also is crisp and lightly fruity.

Bottle. Pours out a cloudy banana yellow colour with a playfully bubbly white head. Scent is mostly yeast interrupted by carbonation. Taste is very astringent with strong yeasty elements. Leaves a wheat taste on the palate that is pleasant as the astringency subsides.

Bottle. Pours out dark brown-molasses colour with a fizzy tan head. Scent is malty accompanied by a grain and skunky hop scent on the backdrop. Taste is skunky hops, maltiness, and lightly roasted maltiness. Leaves an astringent tap water sharpness on the palate but goes down well after it dissapates.

Bottle. Pours out a caramel colour with a very nice foamy and lacy white- bleached bone coloured head. Scent is hoppy with a sweet fruity backdrop. Taste is pleasant and caramel-ish in body... thick and almost sticky. Hops and malt is balanced well to give a nice smooth character. Lacking a wee bit in hop character to justify it as an IPA but very pleasant and drinkable overall.

Bottle. Pours out a deep amber-brown colour with a thick foamy lacy tan head. Scent is mildly skunky and sourish with a chocolate backdrop. Taste is malty with definite skunky hop elements. Is slightly sharp and tart on the palate with a nice malty residue left as it goes down.

Bottle to pounder (shaker). Pours out a caramel-brown colour with a nonexistant head. Nose is warm with caramel and chocolate elements nested on a tap water scent. Flavour is light and weak with very mild hoppiness that is overwhelmed by creamy caramel and malt. Leaves a nice floral and malty residue on the palate. A bit weak and lacking in character but drinkable nonetheless.

Bottle into pounder (shaker). Pours out an orange-amber colour with good clarity. Nice bubbly head that dissapates quickly. Scent is very earthy and hoppy intermixed with general sweetness. A backdrop of water is present (seems to be a common element in Schell beer). Taste is sweet and hoppy with a strong caramel character. Leaves a very floral taste on the palate.

Bottle. Pours out a bright gold, almost banana colour. Very cloudy with a nice bubbly head. Scent is very estery with wheat and yeast elements. Taste is very full-bodied and yeasty with a palate of citrus elements.

Bottle to pounder (shaker). Pours out a nice amber/gold colour with a bubbly head that slowly recedes. Scent is obviously hoppy with citrus and grain in the backdrop. Taste is grainy with hops balancing it out... Not very bitter for an IPA but very drinkable. Taste is nice and palateable with nice hoppy/ citrus/ grain/  grassy earthiness that carries on into and through the finish.  Nice balance but not too much character.

Bottle. Pours out a deep caramel colour with a nonexistent head. Scent is caramel and a slight urine character. Taste contains elements of chocolate caramel and a nice hoppy bitterness... Unfortunately each of these elements is seperated and there is little activity in the glass. Aftertaste is sweet and almost sticky- leaving bitterness on the palate.

Bottle. Pours out a nice golden colour with a playful bubbly white head. Scent is very skunky with light metallic notes. Taste is yeasty with very light fuity notes hanging on the backdrop. Leaves a slight bitterness on the palate. Unexpected flavour elements that seem to have two distinct layers of flavor... One initially yeasty with hanging fruitiness and two a bitter hoppiness with citrus notes. Overall smooth on the mouth and mild bodied.
